# Macro files are Jinja control flow that happens to emit SQL, not SQL. sqlfluff
# parses them as SQL, so its layout rules flatten the {% if %} nesting that makes
# a macro readable, and its capitalisation rules have opinions about identifiers
# that only exist inside a template. Linting them costs legibility and catches
# nothing — a broken macro fails `dbt build`, loudly, which is the check that
# actually applies.
